  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "This design choice enables the detection of UPMEM usage by both VM applications and native applications in the host without requiring any modification to those applications, allowing them to coexist seamlessly with VMs in the vPIM system, thus satisfying requirement 𝑅 3.Data isolation between the VMs is maintained by requiring all rank allocations to go through the manager, which resets rank memory before reassigning it.",
    "Additionally, when UPMEM PIM is used as a memory device, byte interleaving prevents DPU programs from accessing rank memory data.",
    "This hardware feature makes it impossible for a DPU program to read the memory data of another VM when the device is used as a memory resource, thereby effectively meeting requirement 𝑅 2.Currently, vPIM supports spatial sharing at rank granularity due to the lack of hardware support for application colocation.",
    "However, we plan to develop a software-based solution to enable application colocation within ranks.",
    "As the hardware evolves, we anticipate that future PIM hardware will incorporate direct support for application colocation, as suggested in related work [32]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "As the hardware evolves, we anticipate that future PIM hardware will incorporate direct support for application colocation, as suggested in related work [32]."
  ]
